# Text Elements
ie: see Earley's algorithm
we can keep track of each and every possible production we go into when we read an input

and the sets of production and progress in each production after we have read a certain input str
is an 'item'  ^J7rFosuB

kernel items ^YBrApTQR

non-kernel items

can be computed
using CLOSURE
of each kernel items ^F3XPMfqf

production + dot = item ^OrvMWOzw

I = set of items in LR(0)

a state in LR(0) automaton ^nwZkNVj6

GOTO(I_0, '(') = I_4 ^Rs9ZSO4L

Note: we dont differentiate action and goto in
LR(0) automaton because shift and reduce can
be differentiated.

in the LR(0) DFA, GOTO means the transition

transition with terminal: shift
transition with non-terminal:
    no action and just go there 
    if we finish reducing the non-terminal

item with A->B. : reduce ^GQER7VJq

each set of item (state)
has only 1 symbol (terminal/non-terminal)
for all of its incoming transitions

but 2 states can both have the same symbol

It just means that the state each represent 1 symbol 
state implies 1 symbol, but not the other way around

Lets say we went from

I0, I1, I6, I9: it also means we read E + T


the start state I0 doesn't have any incoming edges ^3w5VkEbs

canonical LR(0) collection = {I0, I1, I2, I3...I11} ^tD4UQ8Mk

each is a set of items {[1, 2], [2,1]..} ^3i0UA6YA

production used ^nXqkJ4Z1

position of dot ^xk6VNKi2

this is a shift-reduce conflict in a LR(O) parser (see video).
since it doesnt have a lookahead to decide and instead reduce 
no matter what if we reach this state.
if the next input = *, we don't know which action to take

but not in a SLR(1) parser, since it also takes into account
1 lookahead to decide when to reduce. (Follow(E))

the idea is * ∉ Follow(E),
so we should not reduce when * is the lookahead. ^bF9SfAww

lets say we just finished reading "(E)" and we are here
we must reduce so we should
backtrack to when we first began and read an F  ^JGxHoSIj

read an F ^V02mReic

Note: 
- this is why we must pop the stack len(body/handle) in a SLR parser we implement later
- this is also the only place we read a non-terminal (in a reduce action)
    and we can seperate out the actions for terminal and non-terminals
- we also realise that we do shift/reduce actions only after reading a terminal, 
    a non-terminal is read only after backtracking as part of a single Reduce action
 ^CyXNKj0s

LR(0) automaton: GOTO (terminal/non-terminal)
 ^au9DSEny

SLR(1) parsing table: ACTION (terminal) + GOTO (non-terminal) ^dPcLobve

same ^x87R6F8l

closure({[E'->.E]}): its just normal DFS, similar to subset construction in NFA->DFA

- keep track of the non-terminals added (boolean array for discovered O(1) access)
- stack stores items added (discovered stack)
- U = {} // stores result of closure({[E'->.E]})


- initially E'->.E is in discovered stack
- while stack not empty: 
    pop item from stack
    add the item into U
    if a non-terminal A is right after . and A is not discovered: // like T->.F
        add all productions of A (like A->B) as A->.B to discovered stack ^QZXVoHY1

canonical collection: set of sets of items (states in the LR(0) automaton) ^wHNHwBQ6

for each set of items: 
compute the next set of states
using GOTO and add them into C if they aren't already inside
ie: getting the next state of the automaton ^NkWvGLFA

Just the same as NFA to DFA subset construction! ^7niqSzsS

GOTO(I, X) = { CLOSURE(B) for all A -> a.XB ∈ I }  ^rIFYQGwO

			"text": "closure({[E'->.E]}): its just normal DFS, similar to subset construction in NFA->DFA\n\n- keep track of the non-terminals added (boolean array for discovered O(1) access)\n- stack stores items added (discovered stack)\n- U = {} // stores result of closure({[E'->.E]})\n\n\n- initially E'->.E is in discovered stack\n- while stack not empty: \n    pop item from stack\n    add the item into U\n    if a non-terminal A is right after . and A is not discovered: // like T->.F\n        add all productions of A (like A->B) as A->.B to discovered stack",
